{{Cyborg}} '''Cyborg art''', also known as '''cyborgism''',<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Art of Cybernetic Union - SERIOUS WONDER|url = http://www.seriouswonder.com/art-cybernetic-union/|website = Serious Wonder|access-date = 2016-01-19|language = en-US|2014-05-16 = |date = 2016-01-19|last = Barbato|first = Massimo}}</ref> is an art movement that began in the mid-2000s in [[United Kingdom|Britain]].<ref>Jeffries, Stuart [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2014/may/06/neil-harbisson-worlds-first-cyborg-artist "Neil Harbisson, the world's first cyborg artist"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 May 2014</ref> It is based on the creation and addition of new senses to the body via cybernetic implants<ref>{{Cite web|title = I Don't Have Artificial Body Parts, I Have Artistic Body Parts|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/neil-harbisson/i-dont-have-artificial-bo_b_6804306.html|website = The Huffington Post|access-date = 2016-01-19|date = 2015-03-12}}</ref> and the creation of art works through new senses.<ref>Else, Liz [https://www.newscientist.com/blogs/culturelab/2012/06/cyborg-makes-art-using-seventh-sense.html "Cyborg makes art using seventh sense"], [[The New Scientist]], 29 June 2012</ref> Cyborg artworks are created by cyborg artists;<ref>{{Cite news|title = They Dance the Body Electric: Cyborg Artists Land in Central Israel|url = http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/culture/leisure/.premium-1.658072|newspaper = Haaretz|date = 2015-05-26|access-date = 2016-01-19|first = Neta|last = Alexander}}</ref> artists whose senses have been voluntarily enhanced through cybernetic implants.<ref>Lee, Jennifer [http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/02/a-surgical-implant-for-seeing-colors-through-sound/ "A Surgical Implant for Seeing Colors Through Sound"], [[The New York Times]], 2 July 2012</ref> Among the early artists shaping the cyborg art movement are [[Neil Harbisson]], whose antenna implant allows him to perceive ultraviolet and infrared colours,<ref>[[NBC]], [http://www.nbc.com/last-call-with-carson-daly/video/neil-harbisson/2815607?onid=144391#vc144391=1 "Last Call with Carson Daly"], 29 September 2014</ref> and [[Moon Ribas]] whose implants in her elbows <ref>Garcia, Gabriella [http://www.hopesandfears.com/hopes/future/technology/216729-the-woman-who-can-feel-every-earthquake-in-the-world.html "The woman who can feel every earthquake in the world"], "[[Hopes&Fears]]", 17 de octubre 2015.</ref> allow her to feel earthquakes and moonquakes.<ref>Davis, Sally. [http://nautil.us/issue/1/what-makes-you-so-special/encounters-with-the-posthuman “Encounters with the Posthuman”], Nautilus, 29 April 2013.</ref> Other cyborg artists include:
[[Manel Muñoz]], a Catalan photographer who developed and installed a barometric system in his ears that allows him to perceive [[atmospheric pressure]] changes.<ref>Gabilondo, Pablo [https://www.elconfidencial.com/tecnologia/2017-08-13/ciborg-barometro-oreja-catalan-neil_1426521/ "El catalán que va a implantarse un barómetro para predecir el tiempo: "Quiero ser cíborg"], [[El Confidencial]], 13 August 2017</ref>
Joe Dekni, an artist who has developed and installed a radar system in his head. The sensory system includes two implants in his cheekbones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.momo-mag.com/a-new-cyborg-is-born-by-joe-dekni/|title=A new Cyborg is Born, by Joe Dekni {{!}} momo-mag|website=www.momo-mag.com|language=es-ES|access-date=2018-10-17}}</ref>
